Back then it was common for people to think of rulers/leaders as Gods - usually after their death, but some during. But deifying a guy that might have not even existed?! And Joseph Fiennes...I know your career isn't as good as you brothers right now, but you can do better. text: There's one obvious mistake in one scene that we see in this trailer: A guy testify that he saw Jesus dead for sure and then, he claim he saw THAT SAME MAN alive again.  When you read the Gospel accounts of the Resurrection, it's quite clear that the man the disciples claimed to have seen after Jesus death was lookin' somewhat different than the Jesus they knew, since they had trouble to recognized him!  In fact, it's quite clear that they all needed some kind of sign from the Resurrected Christ to finally recognize him...  In that context, I seriously doubt that someone, right after the event, would have clearly said something like : I saw THAT SAME MAN alive again...  His testimony would surely have been much more prudent and subtle than that.  Also, nowhere in the Christian AND the pagan littÃ©rature of Antiquity we can find any credible account referring to an official inquiry about Jesus' Resurrection by the Romans...  For most of them (including Pilatus), this kind of religious story was probably just one more "Jewish fable" and I'm pretty sure they didn't lose too much time to investigate that.  I have a feeling that they simply concluded the same thing reported in Matthew's Gospel, i.e. that the body had probably been stolen by some followers of Jesus and turn the page about this whole affair.

text: Leaving historical accuracy aside for a moment, this does not even look Biblically accurate. You have the sealed tomb and all that, and that's great, but whats this about an Imperial Visit? Was it really necessary to throw the Shroud of Turin in the movie (the shroud was never mentioned in the bible, and it almost certainly dates back to late-medieval Italy rather than 1st Century Palestine).   This movie seems to be doing exactly what The Passion of the Christ did- telling a story which broadly appeals to Western Christianity (specifically, one that neither offends Evangelical nor Catholic sensibilities). And that's fine, but it is rather boring. I would like to see a movie that tells a more historically accurate version of Jesus (IE the radically anti-Roman, anti-elite Jewish Zealot who sought to create the Kingdom of God in this world). It IS an interesting story, and there are infinite takes on it, however, it seems that Hollywood is backsliding into the comfortable territory of Western Christian Orthodoxy these days, when it used to produce better, unorthodox takes like "The Last Temptation of Christ".

text: Look at this objectively.  Why would a man who was a fraud and liar be  remembered by so many 2000 years later?  Now look at the converse of  this hypothesis:  What if this man is who he said he was and did perform miracles that were witnessed by multitudes of people?  Also, what if as he promised, he busted out of his tomb after three days (with a Roman  military guard outside)?  That would definitely explain much......See  the movie and think about it.      Roman Soldiers guard the Tomb, Matthew 27:62-66    The Roman soldiers sealed the tomb. Then they stood guard for the next three days in four hour shifts of four soldiers each. How many Roman soldiers were there we do not know but it could have been as  many as 50 or more and also a number of soldiers from the temple guard  e.g. Jewish soldiers that worked at the Temple. The stone that closed the entrance was very large and was rolled in a  channel. This channel was sloped so it was easy to close but hard to  open.  Background Reading: The Guards at the Tomb Secure it 27:62 The following day (that is, after the Day of Preparation), the high priests and Pharisees gathered before Pilate 63 and said, â€œSir, we remember how that impostor said while he was still alive, â€˜I will be raised after three days.â€™ 64 Therefore, order the tomb to be secured until the third day, or his  disciples may go and steal him and then tell the people, â€˜He has been  raised from the dead.â€™ Then the last deception would be worse than the  first one.â€ 65 Pilate told them, â€œYou have a military guard. Go and make the tomb as secure as you know how.â€ 66 So they went and secured the tomb by putting a seal on the stone in the presence of the guards. Matthew 27:62-66  More Information: These were regular Roman soldiers. A watch consisted of 4 soldiers  which was changed every four hours. They would die if their prisoner  escaped. These soldiers were not from the temple guard like the group  that came to imprison Jesus.

text: I give them points for trying to make a fresh telling of resurrection,  but in the end this film is uneventful bore. There is nothing in here to hold on to. Characters are one dimensional and they are simply not engaging enough to sympathize with, script offers nothing new plus it is so slow paced that it feels like 5 hour film. Not a single emotion  felt during or after it ended. This film is like a band that plays before main stars at concert halls. Yes, you could see them and kill a hour before the main event, but after it is all over you forget about them even being there.It felt like they were grasping at straws here and failed miserably because it also goes into propaganda mode in the end. 2/5
